SIMPLE: hamper
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hamper
<hw>Ham"per</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧m"p⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Contr.
fr. <ets>hanaper</ets>.]</ety> <def>A large basket, usually with a
cover, used for the packing and carrying of articles; <as>as, a
<ex>hamper</ex> of wine; a clothes <ex>hamper</ex>; an oyster
<ex>hamper</ex>, which contains two bushels.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hamper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hamper
<hw>Ham"per</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Hampered</conjf> <pr>(-p⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hampering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To put in a
hamper.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hamper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hamper
<hw>Ham"per</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hamperen</ets>,
<ets>hampren</ets>, prob. of the same origin as E.
<ets>hamble</ets>.]</ety> <def>To put a hamper or fetter on; to shackle;
to insnare; to inveigle; to entangle; hence, to impede in motion or
progress; to embarrass; to encumber.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hampered</xex>
nerves.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Blackmore.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A lion <qex>hampered</qex> in a net.</q>
<rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>hamper</qex> and entangle our souls.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hamper</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hamper
<hw>Ham"per</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Hamper</er> to
shackle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A shackle; a fetter; anything which
impedes.</def> <rj><au>W. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>Articles ordinarily
indispensable, but in the way at certain times.</def> <rj><au>Ham. Nav.
Encyc.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Top hamper</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>unnecessary
spars and rigging kept aloft.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hamshackle</ent>⟦br⟧
